03863nam a22005535i 9780822398233DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19971997ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223982337 a10.1515/97808223982332doi  a(DE-B1597)554213  a(OCoLC)1229161013  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN3331b.L58 1997 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a808.32211 aLitvak, Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStrange Gourmets :bSophistication, Theory, and the Novel /cJoseph Litvak. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSeries Q00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Delicacy and Disgust, Mourning and Melancholia, Privilege and Perversity: Pride and Prejudice -- t2 Bon Chic, Bon Genre: Sophistication and History in Northanger Abbey -- t3 Kiss Me, Stupid: Sophistication and Snobbery in Vanity Fair -- t4 Taste, Waste, Proust -- t5 Expensive Tastes: Adorno, Barthes, and Cultural Studies -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTheoretically sophisticated: How often has this term been used to distinguish a work of contemporary criticism, and what, exactly, does it mean? In Strange Gourmets, Joseph Litvak reclaims sophistication from its negative connotations and turns the spotlight on those who, even as they demonize sophistication, surreptitiously and extensively use it.Though commonly thought of as a kind of worldliness at its best and an elitist snobbery at its worst, sophistication, Litvak reminds us, remains tied to its earlier, if forgotten, meaning of "perversion"-a perversion whose avatars are the homosexual and the intellectual. Proceeding with his investigations from a specifically gay academic perspective, Litvak presents thoroughly inventive readings of novels by Austen, Thackeray, and Proust, and of theoretical works by Adorno and Barthes, each text epitomizing sophistication in one of its more familiar modes. Among the issues he explores are the ways in which these texts teach sophistication, the embarrassment that sophistication causes the sophisticated, and how the class politics of sophistication are inseparable from its sexual politics. Helping gay, queer, feminist, and other provocative critics to make the most of their bad publicity, Litvak mindfully celebrates sophistication's economy of taste and pleasure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aFictionxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aRhetoric. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398233zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822398233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822398233.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles